13.4 Adapting Pseudo-Count Models to the Experimental Design
Chapter 11 derived and validated three pseudo-count Bayesian agents using the marble task’s original encoding (direct evidence: 0–8 blue marbles out of 8; social evidence: 0–3 pseudo-marbles out of 3). The present dataset differs in two respects:

Social evidence is aggregated from 4 binary responses. We rescale to an equivalent 8-vote sample (\(k_\text{social} \in \{0, 2, 4, 6, 8\}\), \(n_\text{social} = 8\)) so both sources can contribute the same maximum pseudo-counts in the SBA, making the SBA a genuine equal-weighting baseline and the WBA’s \(w_\text{self}/w_\text{social}\) ratio directly interpretable as relative trust.
Extreme self-evidence values are absent by design (\(k_\text{self} \in \{1, \ldots, 7\}\), not \(\{0, \ldots, 8\}\)).

The model mathematics are unchanged; we pass the rescaled counts.

