The diagnostics tell a scenario-stratified story. Drift converges cleanly: zero divergences, R̂ at 1.00, bulk and tail ESS comfortably above 400, MCSE well within tolerance. Static and contingent_shift fail in a structured way: zero divergences and good E-BFMI (so HMC is exploring the energy distribution adequately), but R̂ ≈ 2.9 and ESS in the single digits — the chains are settling in genuinely different regions of parameter space rather than converging on a common posterior.
This pattern is itself diagnostic. The combination no divergences + good E-BFMI + catastrophic R̂ points away from local pathological geometry and toward a global identifiability problem: the chains are exploring a posterior in which some parameter direction is essentially flat, and different chains commit to different positions along that direction. Below we will see that the offending direction is the population mean of log_lambda, and that the failure pattern maps cleanly onto how much information each task carries about decay.
A note on what we report. Because R̂ for the static and contingent_shift fits is far above any acceptable threshold, the posterior summaries from those runs should not be read as valid inference about the true population. We present them anyway because the failure pattern — visible in the recovery plots below — is part of the lesson: hierarchical pooling propagates identifiability problems from the individual level upward rather than fixing them. So there’s that for lazy attempts to fix a problem :-)


