Reading the population-level plot. pop_log_c_mean, pop_logit_bias_mean, and pop_logit_w_mean recover cleanly across all three scenarios: posteriors are concentrated near the simulation truth and well-separated from the prior. pop_log_lambda_mean is where the scenarios diverge. Drift produces a tight posterior centred near the truth — the recovery one would hope for. Static pulls strongly toward the left tail, with mass piled around values much smaller than truth: with no boundary changes, every subject’s data is consistent with near-zero decay, and the population mean is dragged in that direction. Contingent shift is worse than drift but better than static: the posterior is broad and lumpy, sometimes bimodal, spreading across most of the prior range without concentrating on the truth. That ragged, multi-peaked shape is not a kernel-density artefact — it is the visible signature of the R̂ ≈ 2.9 failure. Different chains end up in different parts of the (mean, SD) population-parameter space, and overlaying their draws produces several local peaks rather than a single mode. With proper convergence we would expect a smooth unimodal density; what we see instead is the geometry of an under-identified hyperparameter.
Reading the subject-level plot. The log_c row tells a uniformly successful story: posterior means track the identity line in all three scenarios, with reasonable uncertainty. Partial pooling for \(c\) works as intended.
The log_lambda row is the diagnostic. Under static, every subject’s posterior collapses to roughly the same value (~−2.7) regardless of their true \(\lambda\) — true values span more than three log-units but estimates do not. This is shrinkage without signal: when individual data carry no information about decay, partial pooling drags every subject to a single (mis-estimated) population mean, erasing genuine individual differences. Drift behaves as a hierarchical model is supposed to: posterior means follow the diagonal with sensible uncertainty intervals. Contingent shift sits between the two — there is a positive correlation between truth and estimate, but estimates are heavily compressed toward a central value and the credible intervals are wide. Some signal exists; it is not enough to anchor either the individual estimates or the population hyperparameters.
The lesson. Compare these three columns and the message is hard to miss: hierarchical pooling helps when the population distribution is itself identified, which requires that some individuals contribute information about the parameter in question. Drift satisfies that condition for \(\lambda\); contingent shift satisfies it weakly; static does not satisfy it at all. The multilevel model does not solve the \(\lambda\) identifiability problem — it makes the problem visible at both levels of the hierarchy simultaneously, and it shows what happens when you ask partial pooling to do a job the data cannot support.


14.4.9 Multilevel Simulation-Based Calibration (SBC)
Multilevel SBC is the most rigorous way to check that the hierarchical priors and the non-centered parameterisation are working as intended. Because fitting a multilevel model hundreds of times is computationally intensive, we provide the code here as a template for students wishing to perform an exhaustive validation of their own hierarchical extensions.


