14.4.10 Lessons for analysing real categorization data
The simulations in this chapter are deliberately controlled, but several of the patterns we observed translate directly into guidance for fitting the decay GCM to empirical data.

Identifiability is parameter- and task-specific. \(c\), \(w\), and \(\beta\) recovered cleanly across all three scenarios at both the individual and population levels. \(\lambda\) recovered only when the task itself contained the non-stationarity that decay is supposed to explain. Before fitting, ask whether your design exercises the mechanism each parameter governs — if not, expect that parameter to be pinned by the prior and report it that way.
Hierarchical pooling is a magnifier, not a fix. When individual data inform a parameter, the multilevel model sharpens both individual and population estimates (drift). When they do not, partial pooling collapses every subject to a single, poorly-estimated population mean and the chains stop converging (static, contingent shift). If pop_log_lambda_mean shows lumpy or multi-modal posteriors, R̂ ≫ 1.01, or single-digit ESS on real data, the diagnosis is almost always that the task is closer to “static” than the analyst assumed — not that the sampler needs more iterations.
Computational cost scales with subjects × trials. Each leapfrog step touches every trial of every subject, so wall time grows linearly in both. A 10×64 toy and a 100×200 study differ by ~30× in cost — manageable, but worth budgeting before launching a full hierarchical fit, especially when running diagnostics like SBC that require hundreds of refits.

The next two chapters apply the same pipeline to prototype models (Ch. 14) and rule-based models (Ch. 15), which make different commitments about how categories are represented and updated. The contrasts at each pipeline stage — particularly representation and learning — are the central theoretical content of those chapters.







